      "rationale": "Mesh independence study conducted (see hasVerificationActivity) but GCI computation incomplete for two of five operating points due to solver convergence issues on fine mesh. Discretization error contribution not formally bounded. Achieved level 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental boundary conditions match COU operating envelope; fluid temperature, hematocrit, and inlet velocity profiles documented and matched in simulation.",
      "rationale": "Published FDA pump experiments used bovine blood at 37°C; COU involves human blood at physiological conditions. Hematocrit and viscosity differ. Inlet velocity profiles approximated as uniform; experimental profiles not available. Achieved level 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric (e.g., E% or U95) computed for hemolysis QoI; systematic bias characterized and within acceptable tolerance.",
      "rationale": "Mean absolute error of 34% observed across operating points with systematic over-prediction. No formal validation metric threshold was pre-specified. Bias not attributable to a single identifiable source. Achieved level 1."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation QoI (NIH) is identical to or directly translatable to the COU decision QoI; no surrogate QoI substitution.",
      "rationale": "Validation uses NIH which is the same QoI as COU. However, the hemolysis model was calibrated on Lagrangian particle-tracking data and applied in an Eulerian framework for COU; this substitution introduces unquantified model form uncertainty. Achieved level 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
